######################################################################
# I split all the necessary configurations to external include files #
######################################################################

include $HOME/.config/i3/appearance.conf
include $HOME/.config/i3/keys.conf
include $HOME/.config/i3/rules.conf
include $HOME/.config/i3/workspaces.conf

######################################################################
# why so bare? why so few includes for that matter?                  #
######################################################################
# simply put, i3 allows you to add external include directives files #
# for various settings pertaining to i3-wm itself. It keeps things   #
# from getting way, way too cluttered and in dubious order. Catch is #
# you still need at least the default "config" text file to keep the # 
# includes. As for why I only have four inclues? I prefer to use a   #
# third-party hotkey daemon called sxhkd -- bad name, great utility  #
# for setting all of your hotkeys separate from your window manager. #
# as for the lack of includes; I'm a simple man, I don't use any bar #
# or system tray for stuff I know the terminal and notifications     #
# excel at keeping up to speed with. I use xinit like most others.   #
######################################################################
